segments.text: Okay, you were giving impressions of Dr. Calhoun.
My relationship with him started in the early 60s, and the Department of Commerce,
when I was a guest at the Department of Commerce, started what they called an Office of Technical Services,
and what they would do is they would provide you funding to answer inquiries from industry in your state.
So Dr. Calhoun created at that time what he called the State Technical Services Institute.
He asked me to serve as director of that, which I did.
And so I had some connection with him, but the real connection, I guess,
comes with the Sea Grant Program that I had there.
I had quite a hunk of that Sea Grant Program at one time,
and that came down there in the late 60s as well, so it had to be from 6 to 3.
And I did a lot of work with the Sea Grant Program.
I used my industrial economics staff, which would be perfect.
It would be all economic studies along the cone, things of that nature.
And... OTS had gone out of business, by the way.
Office of Technical Services had gone out of business,
so then I got in on the Sea Grant Program, and of course we run all those things.
So that's really the period between 65 and 73 is when I got really close.
Make believe that I had never seen John Calhoun.
Describe him physically and his style of...
I wish I had a picture.
I could just give it to you.
Dr. Calhoun was...
probably the most diversified, intelligent individual that I had.
Dr. Calhoun could grasp things rapidly.
He did a lot of reading on these things before I come in contact with him or not,
but I mean, he was always very well versed.
My experience with him was through the State Technical Services and Sea Grant Program.
He was a very easy person to talk to.
I never had seen Dr. Calhoun.
Now, some people have seen Dr. Calhoun mad.
I've never seen him mad.
Never had in my life.
Some different things.
We attended a lot of conferences together.
I did a lot of studies.
Then one day out of a clear blue sky in 1973, on a Thursday afternoon, I was working away,
and I got this phone call from Dr. Williams.
And Dr. Williams said, you know, now, I believe I've told you before,
I was having my industrial conference start Monday,
and I had the governor coming over to give the welcome address, which I had every year.
And Dr. Williams said, Jim, I'd like to talk to you in just a few minutes.
And he did.
By now, for one or two, it was a fine.
I went down to his office, and after about five minutes of shaking hands and things,
he said, you know, we have a vacancy as director of the Indian Education Service,
and we want to create an office for Indian education.
And he said, I'd like for you to head for the office.
Now, tell me about this man, Jack Williams.
Well, of course, Jack Williams and Dr. Calhoun were very close, business-wise.
I don't know about personal-wise, but they were always there.
They had a lot of respect for each other.
So I said, well, Dr. Williams, I don't know.
I didn't even know there was a vacancy.
I had the job, but I really enjoyed it.
It was getting bigger every day, and it was getting more statewide and that, the recognition.
I said, I'd have to think about it a little bit.
He said, well, do you need anything to think about?
I said, yes.
I said, I want a copy of the budget.
I said, what kind of budget do they have?
Where are their sources of money coming from?
He got on the phone.
So he got on the phone, and he called Fred Benson, if I'm not mistaken.
It might have been Calhoun, but he called somebody and told him he had been dragged in.
I'd like you to get some budgets up here for the engineering pension service.
And so he told them.
How did that happen?
And so we just did a few minutes.
He said, well, when do you think we can get back together?
I said, we'll get back together Monday morning.
I have all Saturday and Sunday.
We'll get back Monday morning.
So he said, well, just give me a ring Monday morning.
And then we're ready.
Some reason just kept him without it.
And I didn't get a chance to get them together until about 3 o'clock that afternoon.
But I went there, and I told him what my problem was.
And I had, you know, if I did anything, you know, if I want to do this, I need this.
I need this.
I need this.
I need this.
I need this, this, this.
Got down to the bottom line.
The most important thing, I had to have total control of all the people in the organization.
And I was going to be fair with them.
I was going to evaluate each one of them.
But if they didn't fit into the organization, if I'm going to plan for this, then we're
going to have to find somebody who will fill that spot.
But anyway, it went on like that.
And I had to listen pretty long.
He said, is that all?
I said, yes, sir.
He said, you haven't asked for nothing.
He said, you haven't asked for nothing?
He said, no.
I think he said, you haven't asked for nothing.
You can't get it.
And so I said, okay.
So then he called Fred Benson in Calhoun and told him that I'd accepted the job.
I guess Calhoun could tell you more about it from now on.
And I couldn't.
As far as you know, he had talked with each of them in day.
Oh, yes.
In day.
In day.
In day.
In day.
In day.
In day.
In day.
Oh, I'm quite sure of that.
I mean, Pastor Williams would have done, you know.
And another thing I had, see, I had a lot of research projects in .
And this was in August when he called me in.
And I told him, I said, I couldn't possibly accept the job for a few months.
Because I had sponsors out here that supported me for years.
And I said, well, that'd be fun.
That didn't bother him any.
Describe the role of the
Sponsor.
You know, it was really hard.
It was hard.
Describe the extension service when you took over.
What was it?
How big was it?
Where was it?
Well, it was in the old American Legion Hall.
Bob Weitz was before you moved out there.
Do you remember that or was it already down when you got here?
I don't know.
I was here.
Do you remember where the headquarters for Bob Weitz was up until just about a year ago?
No, I don't.
You know where the Farmer Student Association building is now?
Uh-huh.
It used to be that old wooden building right across the street.
Oh, across the street.
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.
Over there by the police station.
Yeah.
Well, I didn't know anybody, I didn't know anybody in any of this except Ernie Winochek.
The only reason I knew him, he had gone by in some ways.
And I had met him through Buddy Williams.
He and Ernie were pretty good friends.
But he's the only one I knew.
And so, when I took over, they took action at the October board meeting.
We made the motion, Ms. Wilson seconded it.
This is 7-0.
Yeah, 73.
I took over.
He said it was 73.
But this meeting was in October before the meeting.
And so, when that was announced and it came out in the paper and everything, by the day,
well, by the way, not the night, you know, that he was approved.
The same day I was approved to direct the Engineering Extension Service.
His picture's on the front page of the Eagle on one side and mine's on the other.
And I just saw when they fixed that monument or whatever it was.
But when I went over to the Engineering Extension Service,
it had a budget of about $1.5 million and they had about $50 million.
Where were they based?
Here.
All of them here?
Yeah.
Okay.
At that time.
They were a very, they weren't up-to-date.
And it was not an area that you could find.
They were taught without lesson plans.
They didn't have any technical manuals.
It's a training organization.
But they had 51 employees in the budget.
But their budget come.
One-third come from Texas Education Agency.
One-third come directly from Appropriations.
And then they got one-third of their money from the city.
Well, you've got to realize the Engineering Extension Service was an old organization.
Most of the employees were, you know, first jobs.
Anyway, when it was announced, they had a Dr. Mansfield.
And that was his final person.
But he had been led to believe, either through himself or through Mr. Bearden.
See, Mr. Bearden had been director and he retired.
That he was going to be the director.
Well, by the way, when I become director.
But anyway.
And all of them.
And on the first day after COVID, December 1st, 1973.
I'll stay away from that.
July 5th, went in for her third malignancy surgery.
She was operating from that morning.
The first day after COVID.
So.
Two important events.
Very important events.
I stayed with my wife.
Mm-hmm.
I was Dr. Calhoun.
I don't know who that called.
I knew it was COVID.
They knew where I was at.
I stayed with her.
And that was her third surgery.
So, after they got through with the surgery.
They were doing it about five hours.
The doctor went and sent her down to Houston.
Started taking chemotherapy.
Now, I'm not going to dwell on this.
But anyway, after the third operation.
My wife had about all the operations she wanted.
But anyway, they made an appointment for me.
To go see this doctor down in Houston.
Hospital in Houston.
And I got away at the appointment at 1.30 in the afternoon.
My wife and I walked in.
And I checked her in.
And he shut the door.
And I stayed outside.
And about 20 minutes.
About 15 minutes.
He came out.
He said, I'm sorry.
He said, your wife won't let me check.
He said, she's not going to take anything.
Remember?
He said, unless I get to examine her.
He said, it's nothing.
We went in.
He said, come on in.
I said, don't press that.
And I said, are you sure you made up your mind?
He said, yup.
I said, how much do I owe you?
He said, $35.
I wrote him a check.
And that was in 1973.
But going back to the same thing.
I was in the hospital.
I was in the hospital.
I was in the hospital.
I was in the hospital.
Where did primarily geographically, where did, when you took over, where were they
doing the instruction that they were?
They were going out in motels.
No, but where was it?
Was it in the Houston area?
Oh, it was all over the state.
But it wasn't concentrated in one?
No.
No.
See, they was doing all the training for rural electric co-ops.
And they had lineman training and things of this nature.
They did a lot of training for Texas television.
They did a lot of stuff.
Association.
See, they were getting subsidized.
Right.
Give more examples of that.
Okay, law enforcement, water and wastewater.
Fireman Training Center was all part of that?
But they used volunteer instructors.
They only had four people.
Was there one client that was by far the key one, the biggest?
Well, the Rural Electric Co-op, of course, the organization was so small,
they only had...
I'll put this thing in perspective.
Now, wait.
Give me those numbers again.
When I took over, it was around 51, I think, employees.
We had a $39 million budget.
And of that budget, how much did y'all...
Ten percent.
We got $3 million and something in general.
The rest you brought in.
When you started out, you were primarily serving small-town needs,
and the telephone companies were the...
The Rural, uh-huh.
All right, let's see.
When you took over, were there any key office staff members
that you came to rely on?
I'm talking about the people in the office.
I tell you, Dr. Mansfield was a fine person,
and there must have been a shock to his system.
He had a different... His philosophy and my philosophy
was just completely 100% different.
I was used to the soft money operation.
I've always had the soft money.
They didn't like it.
That's their job.
But then another thing I asked Dr. Williams was...
I never did go down to that, but I was up on the eighth floor.
Of the Rudder Tower?
Yeah.
That was my headquarters.
All right, when you took over, in terms of reporting,
you reported to...
Dr. Calhoun.
In which order?
All right, on paper, was it to Benson,
or was it to both on paper?
Both of them.
Okay.
You see, I got funding from community education.
All right, let's go back and talk about this man, Benson.
He's a Kansan, I think, didn't he come?
That's right.
Kansas State, and his...
Tell me about his working style and so forth.
He never did leave.
He walked out.
He wasn't a bit bashful to pick it up and say,
Jim, what's this I hear about so-and-so's?
We had our ground rules set.
I set my ground rules with him.
He told me to inform you or something.
Give me some guidelines.
Because I don't have time to tell you everything I do,
and you don't have time to listen to everything I do.
Give me your guidelines.
You know what Mr. Benson's answer was then?
Keep me informed on the matters you think
that I could have some input on.
Not that, you know, I just never had a reason.
And I can say the same thing about Calhoun.
All right, now, officially, the Extension,
Engineering Extension Service was part of the...
of the Texas A&M University and of the system.
No, the Engineering Extension Service was always a part of the system.
All right.
During those years with Williams and Calhoun and Benson,
did it matter, system or campus?
Did it matter?
And how you operated?
It mattered because I knew exactly what the system was supposed to do.
I knew the policies and procedures of the system.
And I knew what the university was supposed to do.
I knew what I was expected of me in the university.
I knew exactly what I was expected of me in the university.
When you wanted to communicate with them,
whom did you have to go through to get to Calhoun or to Benson?
Nobody except their secretary.
They all, you always, he had the same, they had the same thing with me.
All right.
As you think back on those first years,
what were some key decisions that were made by you or anybody else?
Pertaining to the system?
Or pertaining to the work of the...
Of the Extension, of the Extension, of the...
Engineering Extension Service?
Well, I'm not being derogatory, but I'll make the roll.
I had, you know, the rest of them was all non-degree.
They had one title.
It was all called...
My first thing that I did when I went in there, by January the 1st,
I had a, I even, I had no pay rings.
Everybody made the same.
So the first thing we did, we gave them something to...
And then in February of that year, I had a meeting in Wyandale
to give them a copy of what I call Management by Objective,
and how we was going to run the Engineering Extension Service
and what part they was going to play.
But anyway, there was a few...
You've got to remember, this was an old organization.
They'd all been in together.
Here's a damn stranger.
But anyway, after we had that meeting,
none of them understood Management at all.
They didn't know what Management by Objective was.
But anyway, we started putting that thing together.
I come into a recommendation with Dr. Williams,
Fred Benson, they had about,
I'd say they had about $500,000.
We'd automatically, if they had the qualifications,
they'd go into this pay status, find somebody that had the qualifications.
But we'd give them each title, training specialist.
Well, it was about key decisions.
Okay.
That's how the decisions were made.
And then once we got that thing in line,
and unfortunately, poor old Gotham fans knew it,
but he didn't buy that certain phase, whatever you want to call it, out.
And I brought in a new man as associate director.
I brought in Milt Radke, right off.
He was a young engineer.
And how do you spell his last name?
Radke, R-A-D-K.
He was a TTI.
And how did he come about being in us?
TTI was getting into public work training.
Well, I had created a center for public work.
And I picked up the paper one Saturday morning.
There was TTI announcing they were public work training.
So I got a hold of Fred.
I said, Fred, we've got a problem.
He said, what's the problem?
I told him, I'll take care of that Monday morning.
We had Jack Keese in.
In all fact, you can get out of public work.
That's an extension I kicked in.
That's not a research activity.
And so Milt and Radke was in that position.
We transferred him and one other TTI staff member,
their whole team.
And it turned out that Milt was a very, he's a very good engineer
and a very smart individual and a very, very good writer.
So I brought him on as associate director.
Well, that made all the rest of them.
I didn't do it by all.
He's there a year, a year and a half.
You know, I'm serving him for a time.
But that's how that got started.
But when you have to have a decision made,
it took me less than five minutes to get it.
I could call Benson.
He'd say, well, what did you do?
Or what do you want to do?
Or I could call Calhoun.
Calhoun wasn't as quick on the draw as Benson was,
but he was still very quick.
You know what I mean?
I mean, I'd have more conversation with Calhoun
than I would with Benson.
I mean, it's a good thing.
Did you ever get the impression that,
either one of them ever made a snap judgment
without thinking it through?
I'm sure there are quite a few of us.
I think everybody that's done that.
Let's see.
Back to other decisions.
Because you're in charge for 19 years,
Other decisions that you now look back on and say,
those were key decisions we made.
Well, one key decision we made,
we had a reputation.
And again, it's not something they should never talk about.
But mind you,
at the time of thefast election,
it was a special election.
It's a waste of time.
And so every board member on the board
was putting an effort to support that.
They were calling on the state to find,
I could contact every legislator with one phone call.
So I said, that's our fate.
So the first thing I did,
I put about $150,000 in our department.
We don't have any training aids out there or exhibits.
Okay, what is electronics?
But I had a man in electronics.
All these people I was telling you were fine people, and that wasn't the problem was with them.
So I replaced him right off with Dr. Lloyd Fite.
F-I-T-E.
He would already call me up one day.
I took Lloyd over, and it was half-time.
We'd done this thing, and that was in February.
It was half-time.
It was September 1st.
He'd been a little sold out, and we had it out to greet him.
And so we then started getting pretty heavy on electronics, and we got that thing built up.
We had a gentleman and me in the auto office.
That was one time, and the same gentleman was over at the electric co-op training and the Texas Telephone Association training.
When he retired, I saw that was my strength coverage.
And in the meantime, I got to be very, very well.
And they were lobbying for me.
The rural electric co-ops would take the engineering and maintenance service with their lobbyists.
Same thing with the Texas Telephone Association.
That's what drove everything.
And you're not rural electric, but you've got others.
So we'd start timing, and then we'd keep going.
We'd start tying in with several others.
We got all their training materials.
They'd give me everything, their training materials.
But at that time, see, not a lot of people had nothing.
So we got that from the telephone training.
Then we started getting the powertrain, electric power.
The rural electric co-op didn't have any, but Houston Light and Fire at that time had plenty.
Texas, the big one that really helped me out on my electric training was Texas Fire and Light.
So that's how we built the thing.
And then after, you know, we were driving real fast.
And if they had no growth potential, we'd maybe ought to take them out, which we did.
We did away with three or four divisions.
What were they?
They were always one-man operations.
We had, well, one thing we did, fire was half hazardous material.
And I took that directly away.
It started a hazardous system.
But Al Sterling, the very fine guy, had his master's degree from MIT.
When he retired, we brought him up here.
We broke the divisions off and put that under fire.
We did the same thing with,
with management training.
We used to have, we used to have two levels of management training.
This was a very bold level.
Then we just started moving to a higher level.
It was a supervisor training.
So we had to let, so I let that lower division just go.
We just started what I call supervisor training.
And I'm sure there's five or six others, but I'm right off hand.
I don't remember them all.
But we ended up, we started out, we had five divisions.
We ended up with 17.
Our staff, the professionals first, is we supported them.
We were about, see now that staff first had to do a lot of work
while those people were traveling all over the state of Texas.
And they had to have strong staff people.
But it was about four of them or something.
Where, in the areas where you all worked,
in what area, what work area, subject area,
was it easiest to raise money,
and which one was most difficult to support?
Well, it was all, there was no difference.
Let me just tell you why.
We started Simmons about ten years after I got there.
About in 78, 79, I put in my first center in San Antonio.
It was called South Central Texas Regional Training Center.
And at that time, Henry Cisneros was on the city council,
and then Lenny made the merits.
They had a program over there under the junior college,
and they were totally unhappy with the city funding.
And they were totally unhappy with it.
So the guy, the president of the junior college over there,
Mr. Dr. Wheeler, so they asked me to take it over.
I said, you know what, I'll go talk to him.
Well, I'll go talk to him.
And he was happy as a lark to get it to me.
I said, I can't get along with him.
But anyway, he had about a $300,000 a year program with him.
And so then when we took over South Central Region Training Center,
he was like, give us, you know, whenever I did anything like that,
you know, I'll give everyone what they need.
You've got to provide me facilities.
I mean, we can't rent them.
We don't mean that.
We mean we want facilities built.
If you want these things to come in,
we have to look the part and play the part.
And so we got real nice facilities.
We got the EDA grant.
And the man in San Antonio gives 20 acres of land to build it on.
But anyway, we turned out to have a big thing.
So then when they redid the hemisphere area,
they wanted us to concentrate on electronics in that area.
So they built this beautiful big building, you know,
right there in the chemistry area.
And we had a one 25-year lease.
And before I left, I got two 25-year leases for 75 years.
But when we put that in, that was our first cylinder.
When I left, that thing had about a $2 million in it.
So then the next thing I went in was North Texas,
in Arlington.
We went all over Arlington.
And the next cylinder was in the West Texas area.
That was Adelaide.
Now, all these people were purchasing us these facilities.
You can just see, then Houston.
We went into the Houston area about the same time we went into Arlington.
